      <title>Report Ready PDF tables with rmarkdown, knitr, kableExtra, and LaTex</title>
      <dc:creator>Shannon Pileggi</dc:creator>
      <link>https://www.pipinghotdata.com/posts/2022-01-25-report-ready-pdf-tables-with-rmarkdown-kableextra-and-latex</link>
      <description>


&lt;div class="figure"&gt;
&lt;img src="C:/Users/pileggis/Documents/gh-personal/pipinghotdata_distill/_posts/2022-01-25-report-ready-pdf-tables-with-rmarkdown-kableextra-and-latex/rmarkdown_wizards.png" alt="Rmarkdown. Text. Code. Output. (Get it together people.) Two wizard creatures reading a recipe and mixing potions in black cauldrons to produce a report." width="1988" /&gt;
&lt;p class="caption"&gt;
(#fig:thumbnail)Artwork by &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/allison_horst?lang=en"&gt;&lt;code&gt;@allison_horst&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h1 id="tl-dr"&gt;TL; DR&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Customizing tables in PDF output is possible with &lt;a href="https://yihui.org/knitr/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;code&gt;{knitr}&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; , &lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/kableExtra/vignettes/awesome_table_in_pdf.pdf" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;code&gt;{kableExtra}&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and a bit of LaTeX. Recent updates available in &lt;a href="https://www.danieldsjoberg.com/gtsummary/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;code&gt;{gtsummary}&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; 1.5.1 also allow users to more easily take advantage of these features in summary tables.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id="packages"&gt;Packages&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This material was developed using:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
&lt;thead&gt;
&lt;tr class="header"&gt;
&lt;th&gt;Software / package&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;th&gt;Version&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/thead&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr class="odd"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;R&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;4.1.1&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr class="even"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;RStudio&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;351 “Ghost Orchid”&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr class="odd"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;code&gt;rmarkdown&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;2.11&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr class="even"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;code&gt;knitr&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;1.37&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr class="odd"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;code&gt;kableExtra&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;1.3.4&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr class="even"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;code&gt;tinytex&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;0.34&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr class="odd"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;code&gt;gtsummary&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;1.5.1&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr class="even"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;code&gt;pandoc&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;2.14.0.3&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;h1 id="background"&gt;Background&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet"&gt;
&lt;p lang="en" dir="ltr"&gt;
Can anyone point me to a good R package that can create tables that are easily outputted in PDF. So far every package I have found seems to require numerous external packages and plug-ins in order to output the table as a PDF document. Any advice welcome.
&lt;/p&gt;
— Charlie Harper (&lt;span class="citation"&gt;@charlieharperuk&lt;/span&gt;) &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/charlieharperuk/status/1484149123372793859?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw"&gt;January 20, 2022&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You and me both, Charlie. This is tricky. I tried to avoid the LaTeX route through &lt;a href="https://pagedown.rbind.io/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;code&gt;{pagedown}&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; , but ultimately because I had many tables that varied in size and length, this was not a quick approach.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here is a solution have landed upon; I hope it helps you and others as well. If anyone has additional tips or approaches, please share in the comments!&lt;/p&gt;
